3. Preliminary Results

A. Annual observations of juvenile hares

Fig. 1 shows total the total number of juvenile snowshoe hares trapped and observed each year across all sites.

As can be seen in this graph, number of juvenile trappings were not consistent from year to year. The greatest number trapped was 126 in 1999, the first year of the study. In 2002 and 2009, there were rhares_by_year_min` juvenile observations collected. The mean number of hares trapped by year was 31.5. While this appears to show a downward trend in juvenile hare population, the trend could also be a result of less offort put into data collection. Going forward, researchers should be be consistent about how many traps are set out and how often theyre checked to ensure accurate representations of snowshoe hare populations.

B. Weight comparison and descriptive statistics

Fig. 2 compares the mean weight (g) of male and female juvenile snowshoe hares across the three collection sites. NA indicates that the sex was unspecified.

Across all three sites, male juvenile snowshoe hares had a higher mean weight (g) than females and juvenile hares with unspecified sex. Both mean female and mean male weight was the highest at site bonbs. This seems to show that juvenile male snowshoe hares tend to be larger than females. There were no observations with unspecified sex at this location.

C. Juvenile hare weight difference analysis

According to our results, on average males weigh 90g more than females, with mean weight of 946g and 855g respectively. This difference was determined to be significant (Welchs two sample t-test: t( 325.02) = 2.71, p = 0.01), and the effect size is small-moderate (cohens d = 0.29.
